393. Ophthalmology. 1992 Dec;99(12):1840-7. doi: 10.1016/s0161-6420(92)31715-4.

Functional blindness and visual impairment in older adults from three 
communities.

Salive ME(1), Guralnik J, Christen W, Glynn RJ, Colsher P, Ostfeld AM.

Author information:
(1)Epidemiology, Demography and Biometry Program, National Institute on Aging, 
National Institutes of Health, Bethesda 20892.

PURPOSE: The purpose of this study is to examine the association of 
sociodemographic factors with functional blindness and visual impairment in an 
aged population.
METHODS: Three population-based cohorts (East Boston, MA; New Haven, CT; and 
Iowa and Washington Counties, IA) of persons aged 71 years and older were 
screened for bilateral functional near and distant vision during an in-home 
interview in 1988.
RESULTS: Screening was completed by 5335 participants. The prevalence of 
functional blindness increased with age, from 1% at age 71 to 74 years to 17% in 
those 90 years of age and older. Functional visual impairment increased from 7% 
at age 71 to 74 years to 39% in those 90 years of age and older. In multivariate 
analyses, residence in a nursing home, older age, glaucoma, insulin-requiring 
diabetes at baseline, East Boston site, history of cataract, and lower 1982 
income were independent and significantly associated with both functional 
blindness and visual impairment. Age and nursing home residence were 
significantly (P < 0.05) more strongly associated with blindness (odds ratios 
4.8 and 6.1, respectively) than they were with visual impairment.
CONCLUSION: Functional blindness and visual impairment are quite prevalent among 
the oldest old and the institutionalized. The number of affected individuals 
will increase as the population ages and life expectancy increases. Although 
visual problems are associated with aging, nursing home residence, health 
problems, and socioeconomic conditions, they may be readily remediable and may 
lead to immediate improvements in quality of life.

