404. Med Decis Making. 1992 Oct-Dec;12(4):288-97. doi:
10.1177/0272989X9201200408.

Assessing utilities by means of conjoint measurement: an application in medical 
decision analysis.

Maas A(1), Stalpers L.

Author information:
(1)Nijmegen Institute for Cognition and Information, Department of Mathematical 
Psychology, The Netherlands.

A method is presented for helping patients who have laryngeal cancer to decide 
between laryngectomy and radiotherapy in cases where these treatments are deemed 
medically equivalent. The method is based on the model of additive conjoint 
measurement. The treatment with the higher utility is determined from pair 
comparisons among outcomes that vary in quality and quantity of life. Pair 
comparisons enable a (partial) test of the axioms of additive conjoint 
measurement. This is in contradistinction to earlier work on decision making for 
patients with laryngeal cancer, and most of the work in medical decision making 
in general, in which underlying axioms have almost never been tested. Besides 
testing the axioms, another important advantage of pair comparisons is that they 
avoid difficulties with other, risk-based, assessment procedures by presenting 
only riskless alternatives. Encouraging results have been found in a study among 
patients.

DOI: 10.1177/0272989X9201200408
